1️⃣ “Tell me about your Spring Boot experience”
✅ How to say (BEST ANSWER)

“I have around 2 years of experience in Java and Spring Boot, where I worked mainly on developing and maintaining RESTful APIs.
In Spring Boot, I was involved in controller, service, and repository layers. I implemented CRUD operations, integrated Spring Data JPA with relational databases,
    handled request validation, exception handling, and ensured proper HTTP status codes using ResponseEntity.
I have also worked with application.properties profiles, DTO mapping, and basic Spring Security concepts. I followed layered architecture and focused on writing clean,   
    maintainable code.”

✅ 2️⃣ “What did you do using Spring Boot in your project?”
✅ How to say

“My main responsibility was building REST APIs using Spring Boot.
I created endpoints using @RestController, handled input using @RequestBody, and returned responses using ResponseEntity.
I used Spring Data JPA repositories for database operations and followed service layer architecture for business logic.
I also worked on exception handling using @ControllerAdvice, basic request validation, and debugging issues related to data fetching and API errors.”


✅ 3️⃣ “Explain your project architecture”
✅ How to say (VERY IMPORTANT)

“Our project followed a layered architecture.

Controller layer handled incoming HTTP requests
Service layer contained business logic and transactions
Repository layer interacted with the database using Spring Data JPA
Entity and DTO layers were used to separate database models from API responses

This approach improved code readability, maintainability, and testing.”


✅ 4️⃣ “How do you handle exception and validation?”
✅ How to say

“For validation, I used JSR‑303 annotations like @NotNull and @Size along with @Valid in controller methods.
For exception handling, I used @ControllerAdvice with @ExceptionHandler to manage exceptions globally and return meaningful error responses instead of generic 500 errors.”


✅ 5️⃣ “How do you interact with database in Spring Boot?”
✅ How to say

“I used Spring Data JPA with Hibernate as the implementation.
I created repository interfaces extending JpaRepository and used built‑in methods like save, findById, deleteById.
For complex queries, I used derived query methods and sometimes JPQL.”


✅ 6️⃣ “What real issues did you face in Spring Boot?”
✅ How to say (VERY REALISTIC)

“I faced issues like LazyInitializationException, validation errors causing 400 responses, and incorrect status codes.
We resolved lazy loading issues by using proper fetch strategies or DTO mapping.
I also troubleshooted issues related to incorrect request payloads and handled them through validation and global exception handling.”

✅ This answer looks 100% real — interviewers love this.

✅ 7️⃣ “Have you worked with Spring Security?”
✅ How to say (SAFE VERSION)

“I have basic experience with Spring Security.
I understand authentication and authorization concepts, login flow, and JWT‑based security.
I have implemented role‑based access control in APIs and worked on token validation logic at a basic level.”

⚠️ Never overclaim deep security unless you truly know.

✅ 8️⃣ “How do you write production‑ready APIs?”
✅ How to say

“I ensure proper request validation, meaningful HTTP status codes, exception handling, logging, and DTO usage.
I also avoid exposing entity objects directly and follow clean coding standards for maintainability.”


✅ 9️⃣ “What Spring Boot annotations do you use daily?”
✅ How to say (CONFIDENT ANSWER)

“Frequently used annotations include:
@SpringBootApplication, @RestController, @RequestMapping, @GetMapping, @PostMapping, @Service, @Repository,
@Autowired, @Entity, @Table, @Id, @GeneratedValue, @Transactional, and @ControllerAdvice.”


✅ 🔟 “Why should we hire you for Spring Boot role?”
✅ How to say (FINAL IMPRESSION)

“I have a strong foundation in Spring Boot, a good understanding of REST APIs and databases, and I follow best practices like layered architecture and clean code.
I’m comfortable debugging issues, learning new requirements quickly, and contributing effectively to backend development.
I’m looking to grow further in Spring Boot, microservices, and secure API development.”
